tc) Act 1985 prohibits the possession of alcohol when entering designated sports grounds and from areas where the event may be directly viewed. This includes, for example, entry into football stadia and within sight of the football pitch. The amendment to the definition of alcohol in the 2003 Act will carry over into this Act, so the possession of powdered alcohol will become an offence in these circumstances. Preventing people from taking alcohol, in any form, into football matches or similar places where alcohol is prohibited is a safety and security matter for the venues themselves.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL2570 ; HL2571 ; HL2572 ; HL2574","2016-10-27T13:58:57.467Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619468/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619468/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619468/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-24","Alcoholic Drinks: Sportsgrounds","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what plans they have to prevent powdered alcohol being mixed with soft drinks and consumed in places such as at football matches where consuming alcohol is presently prohibited.","false","Biography information for Lord Brooke of Alverthorpe",,"Lord Brooke of Alverthorpe","HL2575"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619469","Department for Education","false","2016-11-01","<p>We want all pupils to be healthy and active, which is why Physical Education remains a compulsory subject at all four key stages in the national curriculum. The curriculum is designed to ensure that all pupils develop the competence to excel in a broad range of physical activities, engage in competitive sports and are physically active for sustained periods of time.</p><p> </p><p>Academies and free schools are not required to follow the national curriculum but must provide a broad and balanced curriculum. The Government has made it clear that the national curriculum should be a benchmark which academies can use and improve upon.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-11-01T13:18:08.197Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619469/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619469/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619469/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-24","Physical Education: North West","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what percentage of schools in Merseyside and Lancashire have a curriculum which includes physical education.","false","Biography information for Lord Fearn",,"Lord Fearn","HL2576"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619470","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-11-07","<p>Following a refresh of the Mersey Forest Plan in 2014, a boundary change increased the area of the Mersey Forest by 167 km<sup>2</sup> from 1,203 km<sup>2</sup> to 1,370 km<sup>2</sup>, an increase of 13.9%.</p><p> </p><p>The Mersey Forest is supported by Cheshire West and Chester Council, Halton Borough Council, Knowsley Council, Liverpool City Council, Sefton Council, St Helens Council and Warrington Borough Council.</p><p> </p><p>It has reported woodland creation within its boundaries as 17.10ha in the 2013-14 planting season and 25.86ha in the 2014-15 planting season. No figure has been published for the 2015-16 planting season.</p><p> </p><p>The Forest’s web site can be viewed here: <a href="http://www.merseyforest.org.uk/" target="_blank">www.merseyforest.org.uk/</a>.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2016-11-07T14:06:46.013Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619470/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619470/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619470/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-10-24","Mersey Forest","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government by how much the Mersey Forest was extended during (1) 2014, (2) 2015 and (3) 2016 to date; and where new woodland was created as part of that forest.","false","Biography information for Lord Fearn",,"Lord Fearn","HL2577"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619471","The Lord Chairman of Committees","false","2016-11-07","<p>We do not keep figures in a way that makes it possible to compare attendance in a weekly pattern without incurring disproportionate cost. A usual sitting week is 4 days long. So a member who attends 50% of sittings would attend an average of about two days per week spread over a year. In the year ended 21 October 2016 there were 535 current members who attended more than 50% of sittings and 275 who attended 50% or fewer sittings. These percentages do not take account of members on leave of absence, suspended from participating in the House or disqualified from sitting in the House.</p>",,"Lord McFall of Alcluith",,"2016-11-07T17:48:03.357Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619471/answer","Biography information for Lord McFall of Alcluith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619471/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619471/answer",,,,,"200",,"Chairman of Committees (HoL)","2016-10-24","Peers: Attendance","2","House of Lords","To ask the Leader of the House how many of the current members of the House of Lords have attended the House on an average of two days per week during full sitting weeks during the last year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Lord Fearn",,"Lord Fearn","HL2578"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619472","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-11-04","<p>The Government does not hold this information. However, the Inland Waterways Association has compiled a directory of navigable waterways in Great Britain which can be accessed on its website.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2016-11-04T14:51:07.927Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619472/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619472/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619472/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-10-24","Inland Waterways","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many canals were fully self-operating during (1) 2014, (2) 2015, and (3) 2016 to date.","false","Biography information for Lord Fearn",,"Lord Fearn","HL2579"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619474","Home Office","false","2016-11-04","<p>Our priority is to ensure the safety of children during the camp clearance and to ensure unaccompanied children eligible to come to the UK are transferred as quickly as possible. Working closely with the French authorities through an agreed and proper process, and in conjunction with non-governmental organisations (NGOs ) and charities, Home Office officials have interviewed 800 children in the camp who claim to have close family in the UK. Since 10 October, we have transferred almost 200 unaccompanied children to the UK and we expect to transfer many more over the coming days and weeks. We will continue to work with British NGOs as part of this process.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-11-04T09:30:57.65Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619474/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619474/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619474/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-24","Refugees: Calais","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to collect and analyse the lists compiled by British non-governmental organisations in Calais of children and adults who qualify for entry to the UK, and obtain the concurrence of the French authorities to their moving here.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL2580"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619475","Department of Health","false","2016-11-03","<p>The Care Quality Commission (CQC) does not have a statutory role in monitoring the extent of the presence of police at mental health hospitals, or the ethnic backgrounds of those patients in locked psychiatric wards who are involved in incidents with attending armed police officers.</p><p> </p><p>Under the Care Quality Commission (Registration) Regulations 2009, independent sector mental health establishments who are registered with the CQC are required to report, without delay, to the CQC any incident which is reported to or investigated by the police.</p><p> </p><p>Where a patient experiences serious harm or dies as the result of an incident which involved police attending the hospital, National Health Service providers are expected to report such incidents to the National Reporting and Learning System, and independent hospitals to the CQC.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL2582","2016-11-03T13:22:43.007Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619475/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619475/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619475/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-24","Psychiatric Hospitals","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the adequacy of monitoring by the Care Quality Commission of the extent of the presence of police at mental health hospital psychiatric settings.","false","Biography information for Lord Ouseley",,"Lord Ouseley","HL2581"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619476","Department of Health","false","2016-11-03","<p>The Care Quality Commission (CQC) does not have a statutory role in monitoring the extent of the presence of police at mental health hospitals, or the ethnic backgrounds of those patients in locked psychiatric wards who are involved in incidents with attending armed police officers.</p><p> </p><p>Under the Care Quality Commission (Registration) Regulations 2009, independent sector mental health establishments who are registered with the CQC are required to report, without delay, to the CQC any incident which is reported to or investigated by the police.</p><p> </p><p>Where a patient experiences serious harm or dies as the result of an incident which involved police attending the hospital, National Health Service providers are expected to report such incidents to the National Reporting and Learning System, and independent hospitals to the CQC.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL2581","2016-11-03T13:22:43.087Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619476/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619476/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619476/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-24","Psychiatric Hospitals","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what are the expectations of the Care Quality Commission in making publicly available information about the ethnic backgrounds of those patients in locked psychiatric wards who are involved in incidents with attending armed police officers.","false","Biography information for Lord Ouseley",,"Lord Ouseley","HL2582"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619477","Department of Health","false","2016-11-07","<p>This information is not held centrally.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England is working with the National Collaborating Centre for Mental Health and a range of multi-agency experts, to improve acute mental health care through an evidence-based treatment pathway with accompanying commissioning support tools for, planned for completion within 2016-17. Partners are committed to ensuring the work effectively addresses inequalities for people from Black and Minority Ethnic (BME) communities, and a BME reference group comprising individuals with lived experience of using services has been established to provide advice and steer throughout the pathway development process. Following publication of the pathway, implementation will be monitored with particular consideration given to its impact on reducing health inequalities.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England has undertaken an independent patient and service level audit of low and medium secure care services in England (2015 data). An analysis of the data shows that Black and Black British men are uniquely over-represented four-fold (six-fold in London) in secure care mental health services, and experience longer stays in restrictive settings.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England is embarking on a new Secure Care Pathways transformation programme. The aim will be to prevent avoidable admissions to restrictive care by providing support earlier, closer to home, and to support people in their longer term recovery when they are ready to leave secure services. This programme is prioritising the experiences and needs of Black men with mental illness and risk and safety issues in the community. NHS England will undertake targeted engagement with Black men in secure mental health settings, and will co-design with experts by experience, carers, clinicians and providers a community-based Forensic Outreach and Liaison Service, which is particularly accessible and effective for this currently underserved group.</p><p>NHS trusts produced and published their first Workforce Race Equality Standard (WRES) baseline data on 1 July 2015 and the first WRES report <em>NHS Workforce Race Equality Standard – 2015 Data Analysis Report for NHS Trusts</em>, which provides analysis and an overview of data returns by individual trusts, was published in June 2016. A copy of this is attached.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-11-07T14:25:04.54Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619477/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619477/answer","WRES-Data-Analysis-Report.pdf","WRES-Data-Analysis-Report.pdf","WRES Data Analysis Report","WRES Data Analysis Report","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619477/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-24","Psychiatric Hospitals","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what proportions of black and minority ethnic (BME) (1) staff, and (2) patients, there are in mental health hospital psychiatric settings; and what assessment they have made of the extent to which BME patients in such settings are afforded access to equal and fair treatment.","false","Biography information for Lord Ouseley",,"Lord Ouseley","HL2583"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619478","Home Office","false","2016-11-04","<p>The Independent Police Complaints Commission (IPCC) has a strategic objective to improve the confidence of those groups who have least confidence in the police complaints system.</p><p>Key measures for monitoring this are included in their public confidence survey next due to be undertaken in 2017. The most recent survey, undertaken in 2014, shows confidence in the impartiality of the IPCC amongst ethnic minority groups has improved. It is available on the IPCC website at: http://www.ipcc.gov.uk/page/public-confidence</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-11-04T13:38:09.303Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619478/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619478/answer","IPCC_Public_confidence_survey_2014.pdf","IPCC_Public_confidence_survey_2014.pdf","Public Confidence Survey","Public Confidence Survey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619478/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-24","Independent Police Complaints Commission","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of whether levels of trust and confidence of black and minority ethnic communities in the Independent Police Complaints Commission have increased or decreased over the past year; and what evidence they have to support their findings.","false","Biography information for Lord Ouseley",,"Lord Ouseley","HL2584"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619479","Home Office","false","2016-11-03","<p>The Independent Police Complaints Commission (IPCC) has a strategic objective to improve the confidence of those groups who have least confidence in the police complaints system.</p><p>Key measures for monitoring this are included in their public confidence survey next due to be undertaken in 2017. The most recent survey, undertaken in 2014, shows confidence in the impartiality of the IPCC amongst ethnic minority groups has improved. It is available on the IPCC website at: http://www.ipcc.gov.uk/page/public-confidence</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-11-03T17:46:21.123Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619479/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619479/answer","IPCC_Public_confidence_survey_2014.pdf","IPCC_Public_confidence_survey_2014.pdf","PDF of public confidence survey.","PDF of public confidence survey.","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619479/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-24","Office for Police Conduct","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of how the proposed replacement for the Independent Police Complaints Commission, the Office for Police Conduct, would achieve fair outcomes from investigations into alleged police misconduct incidents involving persons from black and minority ethnic communities.","false","Biography information for Lord Ouseley",,"Lord Ouseley","HL2585"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619480","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-11-07","<p>The UK Government is committed to withdrawing from the Common Fisheries Policy (CFP) and putting a new fisheries regime in place. No decisions have yet been taken, although the Government remains committed to sustainable fisheries and the Discard Ban (Landing Obligation), as set out in its manifesto commitments.</p><p> </p><p>The UK is bound by international law, including the United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea (UNCLOS), which gives coastal states rights and responsibilities over their Exclusive Economic Zone (EEZ) and the resources within it.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2016-11-07T14:18:07.897Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619480/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619480/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619480/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-10-24","Fisheries","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend to ensure that, following the UK's departure from the EU, fishing in British waters will be brought under the control of the UK.","false","Biography information for Lord Stoddart of Swindon",,"Lord Stoddart of Swindon","HL2586"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619481","Cabinet Office","false","2016-10-31","<p>The Government is clear that, following our withdrawal from the EU, control of our laws will be brought back to Parliament. All options for ​our​ future relationship​ with the EU​ are being considered ahead of the negotiations​</p>",,"Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen",,"2016-10-31T15:31:08.357Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619481/answer","Biography information for Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619481/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619481/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-10-24","Local Government: Elections","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen on 21 October (HL2113) concerning the right to vote in local elections, whether, following the departure of the UK from the EU, decisions as to who will be entitled to vote in UK local elections will be taken by Parliament, not the EU.","false","Biography information for Lord Stoddart of Swindon",,"Lord Stoddart of Swindon","HL2587"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619482","Department for Education","false","2016-11-03","<p>Sections 406 and 407 of the Education Act 1996 require schools to prevent political indoctrination and ensure the balanced treatment of political issues, including the UK’s membership of the European Union. Schools are aware of these requirements, and it is up to schools to understand their pupils’ needs and tailor their teaching accordingly.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-11-03T15:53:29.697Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619482/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619482/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619482/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-24","European Union: Education","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend to examine material provided by the EU to UK schools and other educational establishments to ensure that it is appropriate in the light of Brexit.","false","Biography information for Lord Stoddart of Swindon",,"Lord Stoddart of Swindon","HL2588"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619483","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-11-03","<p>We are not aware of any indications to date that the UK and Russian suspension of flights to Sharm el-Sheikh is having a negative impact on the security situation there. We are conscious of the economic impact which flight suspension and the resulting drop in tourism continues to have. We look forward to achieving the return of flights once we can be assured that the necessary security environment can be sustained. The safety of British nationals is our main concern.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-11-03T15:34:15.293Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619483/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619483/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619483/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-24","Egypt: Aviation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the security implications of increasing unemployment in Sharm el Sheikh arising from the continued ban on flights between Sharm el Sheikh and the UK.","false","Biography information for Lord Stone of Blackheath",,"Lord Stone of Blackheath","HL2589"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619484","Department of Health","false","2016-11-03","<p>The total cost of all energy supplies, including electricity, gas, oil and coal, to the National Health Service in 2015-16 was reported by the NHS as £570 million. This data is provided as reported by the NHS and has not been amended centrally.</p><p> </p><p>Delivering energy efficiency and generating financial savings for re-investment is the responsibility of NHS trusts locally. Savings can be made through a variety of approaches including better energy management and capital investment in more energy efficient infrastructure.</p><p> </p><p>However, Lord Carter’s Final Report <em>Operational productivity and performance in English NHS acute hospitals: Unwarranted variations</em> published in February 2016 estimated that £36 million could be saved from energy costs by acute NHS trusts through improved efficiency. A copy of Lord Carter’s Final Report is attached.</p><p> </p><p>The Department is working with the NHS to identify the potential for energy savings and providing support where necessary to deliver them. This includes encouraging the NHS to make energy savings through invest to save schemes.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-11-03T13:07:48.267Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619484/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619484/answer","Lord Carter Final Report.pdf","Lord Carter Final Report.pdf","Lord Carter Report","Lord Carter Report","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619484/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-24","NHS: Energy","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what estimate they have made of the total energy costs of the NHS in England for electricity and heating; what steps they are taking to reduce those costs; and what targets they have for such efficiencies.","false","Biography information for Lord Teverson",,"Lord Teverson","HL2590"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619485","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-11-07","<p>The current law requires that all licensed sellers of pet animals, whether they are running a traditional high street pet shop or selling online from their home, do not sell pets at too young an age, which for mammals is defined as before they are weaned or should have been weaned. As part of the licensing review, we are looking to clarify this requirement in the regulations and make it a requirement that both puppies and kittens should not be sold if they are under 8 weeks’ of age.</p><p> </p><p>While we accept that dog breeding needs to be closely regulated, we do not consider that cat breeding requires licensing. If anyone has any concerns about the welfare of animals at a cat breeding establishment they can report the matter to their local authority or the RSPCA. Under the Animal Welfare Act 2006 it is an offence to cause any unnecessary suffering to an animal or to fail to provide for its welfare of which the maximum penalty is an unlimited fine and/or six months’ imprisonment.</p><p> </p><p>We are currently reviewing the laws on the animal activities licensing schemes, including those that control the commercial sale of pet animals, including cats. Earlier this year, we consulted on a number of proposals including one to apply specific welfare conditions to pet vendors. This will mean that such activities will have to be licensed and meet specific welfare standards in order to obtain a licence but there are no proposals to restrict those licensed vendors from selling cats to other licensed establishments.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble","HL2592 ; HL2593","2016-11-07T13:54:48.577Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619485/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619485/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619485/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-10-24","Cats: Sales","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have any plans to prohibit the sale of kittens under eight-weeks old.","false","Biography information for Lord Hoyle",,"Lord Hoyle","HL2591"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619486","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-11-07","<p>The current law requires that all licensed sellers of pet animals, whether they are running a traditional high street pet shop or selling online from their home, do not sell pets at too young an age, which for mammals is defined as before they are weaned or should have been weaned. As part of the licensing review, we are looking to clarify this requirement in the regulations and make it a requirement that both puppies and kittens should not be sold if they are under 8 weeks’ of age.</p><p> </p><p>While we accept that dog breeding needs to be closely regulated, we do not consider that cat breeding requires licensing. If anyone has any concerns about the welfare of animals at a cat breeding establishment they can report the matter to their local authority or the RSPCA. Under the Animal Welfare Act 2006 it is an offence to cause any unnecessary suffering to an animal or to fail to provide for its welfare of which the maximum penalty is an unlimited fine and/or six months’ imprisonment.</p><p> </p><p>We are currently reviewing the laws on the animal activities licensing schemes, including those that control the commercial sale of pet animals, including cats. Earlier this year, we consulted on a number of proposals including one to apply specific welfare conditions to pet vendors. This will mean that such activities will have to be licensed and meet specific welfare standards in order to obtain a licence but there are no proposals to restrict those licensed vendors from selling cats to other licensed establishments.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble","HL2591 ; HL2593","2016-11-07T13:54:48.627Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619486/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619486/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619486/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-10-24","Cats: Animal Breeding","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have any plans to regulate the breeding of cats for sale in cases where a single cat produces several litters.","false","Biography information for Lord Hoyle",,"Lord Hoyle","HL2592"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619487","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-11-07","<p>The current law requires that all licensed sellers of pet animals, whether they are running a traditional high street pet shop or selling online from their home, do not sell pets at too young an age, which for mammals is defined as before they are weaned or should have been weaned. As part of the licensing review, we are looking to clarify this requirement in the regulations and make it a requirement that both puppies and kittens should not be sold if they are under 8 weeks’ of age.</p><p> </p><p>While we accept that dog breeding needs to be closely regulated, we do not consider that cat breeding requires licensing. If anyone has any concerns about the welfare of animals at a cat breeding establishment they can report the matter to their local authority or the RSPCA. Under the Animal Welfare Act 2006 it is an offence to cause any unnecessary suffering to an animal or to fail to provide for its welfare of which the maximum penalty is an unlimited fine and/or six months’ imprisonment.</p><p> </p><p>We are currently reviewing the laws on the animal activities licensing schemes, including those that control the commercial sale of pet animals, including cats. Earlier this year, we consulted on a number of proposals including one to apply specific welfare conditions to pet vendors. This will mean that such activities will have to be licensed and meet specific welfare standards in order to obtain a licence but there are no proposals to restrict those licensed vendors from selling cats to other licensed establishments.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble","HL2591 ; HL2592","2016-11-07T13:54:48.5Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619487/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619487/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619487/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-10-24","Cats: Sales","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have any plans to restrict the commercial sale of cats to licensed establishments to ensure the welfare of cats for sale.","false","Biography information for Lord Hoyle",,"Lord Hoyle","HL2593"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619488","Department for Education","false","2016-11-08","<p>Local Authorities must make young people with Education, Health and Care Plans aware of the support available to them in higher education and how to claim it. Additionally, Student Finance England provides information, advice and guidance for all students about the support available whilst undertaking a course of higher education, including Disabled Students’ Allowances.</p>",,"Viscount Younger of Leckie",,"2016-11-08T15:52:07.28Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619488/answer","Biography information for Viscount Younger of Leckie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619488/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619488/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-24","Disabled Students' Allowances","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to ensure that students with Education Health and Care Plans are being made aware of recent changes to the Disabled Students allowance process.","false","Biography information for Lord Addington",,"Lord Addington","HL2594"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619489","Department for Education","false","2016-11-08","<p>All higher education institutions (HEIs) have a duty to make reasonable adjustments under the Equality Act 2010, and for ensuring they comply with the Equality Act’s provisions in respect of disabled students. The Department is facilitating a sector- led group, the Disabled Students Sector Leadership Group, to provide information to HEIs to help them to respond effectively to the changes. This Group expects to publish guidance shortly.</p>",,"Viscount Younger of Leckie",,"2016-11-08T15:52:36.95Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619489/answer","Biography information for Viscount Younger of Leckie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619489/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619489/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-24","Higher Education: Disability","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what monitoring is being undertaken to ensure that all colleges providing higher education are aware of their duties and responsibilities in bands 1 and 2 support for disabled students.","false","Biography information for Lord Addington",,"Lord Addington","HL2595"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619490","Department for Education","false","2016-11-08","<p>The Equality Act specifically prohibits Higher Education Institutions (HEIs) from refusing to enroll students as a result of their disability. The Department does not hold information on whether HEIs comply with this requirement in particular instances.</p>",,"Viscount Younger of Leckie",,"2016-11-08T15:54:01.51Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619490/answer","Biography information for Viscount Younger of Leckie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619490/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619490/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-24","Higher Education: Disability","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what estimate they have made of the number of potential students with disabilities being refused registration at a college without Disabled Student Allowance support because that college is unable to financially support them.","false","Biography information for Lord Addington",,"Lord Addington","HL2596"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619491","Department for Education","false","2016-11-08","<p>Non-medical support, provided by a higher education institution as a reasonable adjustment under the Equality Act, falls outside the scope of Disabled Students’ Allowances. Therefore, it falls outside the remit of the Disabled Students’ Allowances Quality Assurance Group. As independent, autonomous organisations, higher education institutions are responsible for quality assuring the support they provide.</p>",,"Viscount Younger of Leckie",,"2016-11-08T15:55:31.45Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619491/answer","Biography information for Viscount Younger of Leckie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619491/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619491/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-24","Higher Education: Disability","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether steps are being taken, by the Disabled Students Allowance Quality Assurance Group or otherwise, to quality assure higher education institutions which provide non-medical support to disabled students outside the Disabled Students Allowance system for procuring accredited support.","false","Biography information for Lord Addington",,"Lord Addington","HL2597"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619492","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-02","<p>The UK has an inflation target, not an exchange rate target. The value of sterling adjusts flexibly in response to economic conditions and market forces.</p><p> </p><p>We are going through a period of adjustment as the economy responds to the vote to leave the European Union. The fundamental strength of the UK economy means that it is well-placed to deal with the challenges, and take advantage of the opportunities, that lie ahead.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2016-11-02T16:15:10.23Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619492/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619492/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619492/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-24","Sterling","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their assessment of the recent fall in the value of sterling.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL2598"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619493","Department for Education","false","2016-11-03","<p>The judgment in the Ashers Bakery appeal was made in accordance with the equality law that is in force in Northern Ireland rather than the Equality Act 2010 which applies in the rest of the UK. Any consideration of the issues raised in that case is therefore a matter for the Northern Ireland Assembly in the first instance.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-11-03T15:51:29.99Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619493/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619493/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619493/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-24","Homosexuality: Northern Ireland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, following the decision in the Ashers Bakery appeal, whether they intend to speak to the First Minister and the deputy First Minister of Northern Ireland on the issues raised in that case.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL2599"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619494","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-11-07","<p>The number of fatal injuries in the agriculture sector fluctuates each year, and as such it is not possible to draw conclusions from figures for individual years. The annual number of deaths averaged over a five year rolling period is broadly static and remains a cause for concern for the Health and Safety Executive, the Farm Safety Partnerships (FSP) in England, Scotland and Wales, the Agriculture Industry Advisory Committee (AIAC) and the industry itself.</p><p>The Health and Safety Executive publishes figures on health and safety in the agriculture sector in the attached document “Statistics on fatal injuries in the workplace in Great Britain 2016”. Further information can also be found in the published report “Health and safety in agriculture, forestry and fishing in Great Britain, 2015/16”, which is also attached.</p>",,"Lord Freud",,"2016-11-07T16:01:20.433Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619494/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619494/answer","HL2600 - Statistics on fatal injuries in the workplace in Great Britain 2016.pdf ; HL2600 - Statistics on fatal injuries in agriculture, forestry and fishing in Great Britain 2015-16.pdf","HL2600 - Statistics on fatal injuries in the workplace in Great Britain 2016.pdf ; HL2600 - Statistics on fatal injuries in agriculture, forestry and fishing in Great Britain 2015-16.pdf","Statistics on fatal injuries in the workplace GB ; Statistics on fatal injuries in agriculture etc","Statistics on fatal injuries in the workplace GB ; Statistics on fatal injuries in agriculture etc","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619494/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-24","Agriculture: Industrial Health and Safety","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their latest assessment of health and safety in the agricultural sector.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL2600"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619819","Cabinet Office","false","2016-10-27","<p>Workforce planning, including apprenticeships, is the responsibility of individual departments.</p><p>However, in light of the Government’s manifesto commitment to achieve three million new apprenticeship starts in England by the end of the Parliament, the Cabinet Office will be collecting data on apprenticeships to allow the Civil Service to report on our contribution towards the national target. From 2016/17 onwards, apprenticeship data will be collected on a quarterly basis.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2016-10-27T12:42:49.93Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619819/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619819/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619819/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-10-24","Apprentices: Government Departments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many apprenticeships have been created in each Government department in each region in each of the last five years; and how many of those apprentices subsequently secured a job within the Civil Service.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","49829"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619820","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-10-27","<p>Since the Cyber Essentials scheme began it is estimated that 377 organisations have been certified more than once. This includes organisations that have both Cyber Essentials and Cyber Essentials Plus certificates, as well as those that have been certified more than once with different IT systems in scope.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-10-27T15:13:23.507Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619820/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619820/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619820/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-24","Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many organisations have recertified (a) Cyber Essentials and (b) Cyber Essentials Plus in each year since each scheme's creation.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","49949"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619822","Cabinet Office","false","2016-10-27","<p>The Office of Cyber Security and Information Assurance (OCSIA) has been fully funded by the National Cyber Security Programme (NCSP) since its establishment. There have been no underspends in OCSIA funding.</p><p> </p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2016-10-27T12:45:00.507Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619822/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619822/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619822/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-10-24","Office of Cyber Security and Information Assurance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what underspend the Office of Cyber Security and Information Assurance has had in each year since its establishment.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","49950"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619823","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-10-27","<p>The Cyber Governance Health Check (published 2015) found that 58% of FTSE 350 companies had assessed themselves against the Government’s ‘10 Steps to Cyber Security’ guidance, up from 40% in 2013. The 2016 Cyber Security Breaches Survey found that 29% of large businesses [those with 250+ employees] are aware of the ‘10 Steps…’ guidance. The guidance has been viewed over 40,000 times.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-10-27T15:15:49.543Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619823/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619823/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619823/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-24","Cybercrime: Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many (a) FTSE 100 and (b) FTSE 350 companies have used the 10 Steps to Cyber Security guidance to date.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","49966"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619824","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-10-28","<p>So far, 23 individuals are participating in the current programme which started on 12 September.</p><p> </p><p>The early stage accelerator programme, called HutZero, is part of the Government’s strategy to promote the UK cyber security industry, and is designed to transform early stage ideas into workable proposals and potential new businesses. The programme supports individuals at the very start of their entrepreneurial journey.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-10-28T09:26:17.06Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619824/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619824/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619824/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-24","Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many start-up businesses have participated in the Early Stage Accelerator programme since it began.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","49954"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619825","Cabinet Office","false","2016-11-01","<p>Triggering Article 50 falls under the prerogative executive power, the powers exercised on behalf of the sovereign by ministers. Triggering Article 50 is something for the Government to get on with. Parliament had its say in legislating for the Referendum, which it did in both Houses, and with cross-party support by a margin of 6 to 1. Parliament was clear it was for the people to decide whether to remain in the EU or leave it. The people have spoken, and it is now down to the Government to act on their orders.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2016-11-01T08:53:54.457Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619825/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619825/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619825/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-10-24","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether the Queen's Constitutional prerogative, the legal prerogatives or prerogative executive powers will be used when triggering Article 50 of the Treaty on the Functions of the EU.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","49982"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619827","Cabinet Office","false","2016-10-27","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2016-10-27T12:49:41.667Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619827/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619827/answer","PQ 49961 Attached Table.xlsx ; PQ49961 .pdf","PQ 49961 Attached Table.xlsx ; PQ49961 .pdf","EXcel Table for Member - Causes of Death ; UKSA Letter to Member - Causes of Death","EXcel Table for Member - Causes of Death ; UKSA Letter to Member - Causes of Death","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619827/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-10-24","Death: Manchester","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the five most common causes of death among (a) women and (b) men in each age group in Greater Manchester were in the latest year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Andy Burnham","Leigh","Andy Burnham","49961"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619828","Cabinet Office","false","2016-10-27","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p><p>Zero hours contracts do have a part to play in a modern, flexible labour market – because, for a small proportion of the workforce, that may be the kind of contract that is right for them. On average, people on zero hour contracts work 25 hours a week and nearly 70 per cent of people on zero hours contracts do not want more hours, according to ONS figures. I would note that many Labour councils have used such contracts.</p><p>Notwithstanding, the Government's review of modern employment practices (chaired by Matthew Taylor) will consider zero hour contracts and make recommendations about how to maintain flexibility while supporting job security, workplace rights, opportunities for progression and representation for the growing number of people who do not have traditional employment relationships.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2016-10-27T14:57:30.06Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619828/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619828/answer","PQ 49962.pdf","PQ 49962.pdf","UKSA Letter to Member - Zero Hour Contracts","UKSA Letter to Member - Zero Hour Contracts","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619828/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-10-24","Zero-hours Contracts: Greater Manchester","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many people in each age group in (a) Leigh constituency and (b) Greater Manchester are employed on a zero-hours contract.","false","Biography information for Andy Burnham","Leigh","Andy Burnham","49962"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619829","Cabinet Office","false","2016-10-27","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p><p>I would add that the Government's National Living Wage was introduced in April 2016 for all working people aged 25 and over, and is set at £7.20 per hour. We have asked the Low Pay Commission to recommend the National Living Wage rate that should apply from April 2017, towards a target 60% of median earnings by 2020. By then, around 2.9 million people are expected to have had a pay rise, thanks directly to the National Living Wage. The Government recognises the important work undertaken by the Living Wage Foundation and we encourage employers to pay above the National Minimum Wage or National Living Wage where it is affordable to do so.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2016-10-27T12:41:34.577Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619829/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619829/answer","PQs 49963 .pdf","PQs 49963 .pdf","UKSA Letter to Member - Living Wage","UKSA Letter to Member - Living Wage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619829/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-10-24","Living Wage: Greater Manchester","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many people in each age group in (a) Leigh constituency and (b) Greater Manchester are paid less than the living wage as defined by the Living Wage Foundation.","false","Biography information for Andy Burnham","Leigh","Andy Burnham","49963"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619830","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-10-27","<p>The number of certificates issued by calendar year and by Cyber Essentials and Plus is provided in the table below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Cyber Essentials</p></td><td><p>Plus</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014, from June</p></td><td><p>198</p></td><td><p>35</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>1067</p></td><td><p>191</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016, to end September</p></td><td><p>2188</p></td><td><p>341</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-10-27T15:17:36.503Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619830/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619830/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619830/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-24","Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many organisations held (a) Cyber Essentials and (b) Cyber Essentials Plus certification in each calendar year since 2014.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","49957"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619831","Cabinet Office","false","2016-10-31","<p>There are now legal proceedings underway and it would not be appropriate for the Government to comment further on these at this time.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2016-10-31T10:13:07.337Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619831/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619831/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619831/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-10-24","Royal Prerogative","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether a decision to use the Royal Prerogative to trigger Article 50 of the Treaty on the Functioning of the EU will be subject to judicial review.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","50009"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619833","Department for Education","false","2016-11-02","<p>The Public Sector Equality Duty (PSED) is a key lever for ensuring that public bodies, including executive agencies, already consider the potential impact of their decisions, including decisions about funding allocation, on people who share different protected characteristics.</p><p> </p><p>The PSED requires public bodies, and those carrying out public functions, to have due regard to the need to:</p><p> </p><ul><ul><li><p>eliminate discrimination, harassment, victimisation and any other conduct that is prohibited by or under the Equality Act 2010;</p></li><li><p>advance equality of opportunity, and;</p></li><li><p>foster good relations between people who share a relevant protected characteristic and those who do not.</p><p> </p></li></ul></ul><p>Public bodies must be able to show how equality issues have been considered when they develop, implement, evaluate and review policies, services and processes.</p><p> </p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-11-02T17:23:21.673Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619833/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619833/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619833/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-24","Protected Characteristics","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will make it her policy that executive agencies collect data on funding allocated to people who have protected characteristics as listed in the Equality Act 2010.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","50003"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619834","Cabinet Office","false","2016-10-27","<p>Prerogative powers have changed over time with legislation clarifying the limit and extent as well as in some cases the existence of the prerogative, and as such there is no definitive list. The Cabinet Manual sets out that the bulk of prerogative powers are exercised by Ministers on behalf of the Sovereign which include powers in relation to foreign affairs, to deploy the Armed Forces and to grant mercy.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2016-10-27T12:45:40.367Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619834/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619834/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619834/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-10-24","Royal Prerogative","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will publish a definitive list of prerogative powers currently exercisable by the Government.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","50030"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619835","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-31","<p>Rural Rate Relief provides 50% mandatory relief from business rates. The hierarchy of reliefs requires that a ratepayer must be given Rural Rate Relief over Small Business Rate Relief. The government keeps all taxes under review.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-10-31T15:10:49.607Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619835/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619835/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619835/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-24","Non-domestic Rates: Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what his policy is on extending Small Business Rate Relief to businesses that claim Rural Rate Relief.","false","Biography information for Sir Edward Leigh","Gainsborough","Sir Edward Leigh","49976"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619838","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-27","<p>The process for selecting claims for Concentrix compliance interventions is set out in sections A9 and A10 of the “specifications of requirement” annex of the Concentrix contract. Reasons why Concentrix may not investigate a proportion of those can also be found in section A22.1 of the contract which can be found at: <a href="https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Notice/85d1b730-5e4e-4be8-ae4c-3ac1f359afc7" target="_blank">https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Notice/85d1b730-5e4e-4be8-ae4c-3ac1f359afc7</a></p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-10-27T14:02:45.24Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619838/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619838/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619838/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-24","Concentrix","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the oral evidence given by Philip Cassidy to the Work and Pensions Committee on 13 October 2016, Question 30, what criteria HM Revenue and Customs applied in selecting the 1.5 million high-risk working tax credit claimant records provided to Concentrix in April 2016; for what reasons Concentrix decided not to investigate a proportion of those cases; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","49900"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619840","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-11-01","<p>We are determined to ensure that current and former members of the Armed Forces gain the housing they deserve, recognising the sacrifices they have made for the country in line with the commitment of the Covenant.</p><p>We therefore changed the law by regulation in 2012 to ensure that seriously injured serving personnel and former members of the Armed Forces with urgent housing needs are always given ‘additional preference’ (high priority) for social housing; and councils are prevented from applying local connection requirements to disqualify members of the Armed Forces and those within 5 years of leaving the Services from their waiting list.</p><p>Our 2012 statutory social allocations guidance goes further and sets out how councils’ allocation schemes can give priority to all Service families, including through the use of local preference criteria and local lettings policies.</p><p>We also introduced measures to make it easier for those with aspirations of home ownership to own their own home. This includes giving former Service personnel and their surviving partners priority for government funded shared ownership schemes for 12 months after service which has now been extended to 24 months. They are also able to access Government-funded home ownership schemes including Help to Buy.</p><p>We are also removing the age restriction for eligibility for starter homes which allows homes to be sold at a 20% discount to market value for eligible first time buyers, for injured military services personnel and bereaved spouses.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2016-11-01T15:40:10.303Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619840/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619840/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619840/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-10-24","Housing: Armed Forces","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps he is taking to support current and ex-service personnel to find a home.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","49877"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619841","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-11-01","<p>Information on the costs incurred by local authorities in relation to translating documents and employing interpreters is not collected by the Department.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-11-01T15:35:08.513Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619841/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619841/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619841/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-10-24","Local Government: Translation Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the annual cost to local authorities of translating documents into different languages and employing interpreters.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","49917"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619842","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-11-01","<p>The Local Government Transparency Code 2015 requires councils to publish information about how they use their assets, spend money and make decisions. This increases local democratic accountability and makes it easier for local people to contribute to local decision making. Additionally, local authorities are required, through Section 3 of the Local Government Act 1999, to make arrangements to secure continuous improvement in how their functions are exercised, having regard to a combination of economy, efficiency and effectiveness.</p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-11-01T15:39:11.95Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619842/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619842/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619842/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-10-24","Local Government: Accountability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what guidance his Department issues to local authorities on reviewing the cost of democratic arrangements to ensure that they promote good governance and provide value for money.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","49915"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619843","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-10-27","<p>The Government’s view is that the current selective licensing arrangements are working. The Government does not support unnecessary large selective licensing schemes. Such an approach is likely to be disproportionate and create additional needless costs for reputable landlords which tend to be passed onto tenants. Local authorities can introduce targeted schemes to deal with specific local problems below the threshold of either 20% of their geographical area or 20% of their local private rented sector. Any scheme larger than the 20% threshold must obtain prior approval from the Secretary of State. Of the three applications received since these measures were put in place in April 2015, two have been accepted and one declined. The London Borough of Newham’s selective licensing scheme runs until 2018; should the authority wish to continue the scheme it will need demonstrate that the proposed redesignation meets the statutory criteria as set out in The Selective Licensing of Houses (Additional Conditions) (England) Order 2015.</p><p>On 18 October, the Government announced plans to extend mandatory licensing of Houses in Multiple Occupation (HMO) to strengthen councils to tackle problems homes head-on and bring an end to ruthless landlords who exploit tenants and charge them extortionate rents to live in poor conditions. These measures will ensure mandatory licensing rules apply to HMOs with five or more people, and to flats above and below shops. Minimum room sizes will also apply to HMOs to help to clamp down on rogue landlords cramming tenants into unsafe and overcrowded homes.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2016-10-27T16:17:18.027Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619843/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619843/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619843/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-10-24","Landlords: Newham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the implications for his Department's policies of the Landlord Licensing Scheme introduced by the London Borough of Newham; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","49946"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619845","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-01","<p>The best practice guidance issued by the Department for Transport to local licensing authorities is currently being reviewed and updated. In addition to this, the Government has also introduced an amendment to the Policing and Crime Bill that will enable statutory guidance to be issued on aspects related to the safeguarding of children and vulnerable adults. Both parts of the guidance will be consulted on once the Policing and Crime Bill receives Royal Assent.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-11-01T17:56:08.667Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619845/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619845/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619845/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-24","Taxis: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if his Department will issue new guidance to local authorities on the issuing of Hackney carriage or taxi licences to include higher quality background checks and improved standards.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","49978"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619846","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-11-10","<p>One person without a home is too many. Homelessness robs families of their future, safety and self-worth, and we refuse to accept this. Although only 3% of individuals seen sleeping rough in London are UK nationals with a history of service in the armed forces, this is still too high, and no way to treat our veterans (<a href="https://data.london.gov.uk/dataset/chainreports/resource/6c740944-3816-4f21-bbcf-04505b59c76b" target="_blank">https://data.london.gov.uk/dataset/chainreports/resource/6c740944-3816-4f21-bbcf-04505b59c76b#</a>).</p><p>We are committed to fight for all those who have fought for us. All local authorities in England are signed up to the Armed Forces Covenant, ensuring they support the needs of their armed forces communities. We have committed over £500 million to tackle homelessness over the next four years as set out at the last Spending Review.</p><p>We have also given our support to the Homelessness Reduction Bill, to reform England’s homelessness legislation and ensure that more people get the help they need to prevent a homelessness crisis in the first place.</p><p>We have gone further and announced a £40 million Homelessness Prevention Programme to ensure there is an end-to-end approach to prevent homelessness and rough sleeping, and provide the support people need to recover from homelessness.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-11-10T16:36:03.803Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619846/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619846/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619846/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619846/answer/previousversion/17049","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-10-24","Veterans: Homelessness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the number of (a) veterans sleeping rough and (b) homeless veterans in (i) Liverpool, Wavertree constituency, (ii) Liverpool, (iii) the Liverpool City Region and (iv) each region in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","50027"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619847","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-11-02","<p>The Government is looking very carefully at Professor Waterson’s recommendations and a response will be published in due course.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2016-11-02T13:45:57.06Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619847/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619847/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619847/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-24","Tickets: Touting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to the Independent Review of Consumer Protection Measures concerning Online Secondary Ticketing facilities, published in May 2016, what steps the Government is taking to tackle ticket touting.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","50037"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619848","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-10-27","<p>The Government is making a significant contribution to broadband provision across the UK, and the superfast broadband projects that are under way in the devolved nations will deliver superfast coverage to nearly 700,000 premises in Scotland, 650,000 in Wales and 40,000 in Northern Ireland. These form an important part of achieving 95% superfast coverage across the UK by December 2017. The project in Northern Ireland adds to the previous roll-out.</p><p> </p><p>These projects will also benefit from clawback funding from suppliers as a result of take-up going above the initial expected levels, which will be available for reinvestment in additional superfast broadband coverage. New procurements are under way in each of the nations using this funding which will further increase superfast coverage.</p><p> </p><p>In addition the government is introducing a Universal Service Obligation in the Digital Economy Bill, which will give the right to consumers to request a broadband service; our aim is currently to set this at 10Mbps.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-10-27T11:59:53.71Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619848/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619848/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619848/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-24","Broadband: Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment she has made of the adequacy of rural broadband cover in Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","49956"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619849","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-10-27","<p>As the UK’s independent communications regulator, it is for Ofcom to define the markets that it regulates.</p><p> </p><p>Under the EU Electronic Communications Framework Directive, the national regulatory authorities must analyse their national electronic communications markets, in consultation with the industry, and propose appropriate regulatory measures to address any market failures that might be hampering competition. These findings and proposals must be notified to the Commission and other national authorities, ensuring that the rules are applied consistently in all Member States.</p><p> </p><p>The Commission has established a list of markets for electronic communications that it considers should be the starting point for this national analysis.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-10-27T09:41:30.377Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619849/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619849/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619849/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-24","Ofcom","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 24 October 2016 to Question 49393, what powers she has to set the limits of the markets which Ofcom regulates.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","50017"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619851","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-27","<p>The information is not held centrally and could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-10-27T15:18:16.607Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619851/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619851/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619851/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-24","Ministry of Defence: Social Media","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many civilian personnel in his Department have been subject to disciplinary action for non-compliance with his Department's policies on use of social media in each month since 2010.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","49837"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619852","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-27","<p>The requested information is provided in the attached tables.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-10-27T15:13:21.583Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619852/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619852/answer","20161025-PQ_UIIN_49838_-_social_media_TABLES (1).docx","20161025-PQ_UIIN_49838_-_social_media_TABLES (1).docx","49838 – MOD AF Personnel - Use of Social Media","49838 – MOD AF Personnel - Use of Social Media","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619852/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-24","Armed Forces: Social Media","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many (a) officers and (b) soldiers from the (i) Army, (ii) Royal Air Force and (iii) Royal Navy have been subject to disciplinary action for non-compliance with his Department's policies on use of social media in each month since 2010.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","49838"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619854","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-27","<p>The information is not held centrally and could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-10-27T15:17:32.11Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619854/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619854/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619854/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-24","Ministry of Defence: Misconduct","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many times his Department (a) terminated a contract and (b) imposed a penalty for grave professional misconduct in each year since 2011.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","49841"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619855","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-28","<p>Recruitment targets for the Reserve Forces that include targets for Maritime Reserves have been placed in the Library of the House (DEP2013-2063-20131219).</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-10-28T13:36:34.22Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619855/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619855/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619855/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-24","Royal Naval Reserve","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what recruitment targets his Department has set for the Royal Naval Reserve.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","49857"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619856","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-01","<p>Both initial and specialist training for members of the Royal Naval Reserve (RNR) is conducted alongside training for Regular Naval Service personnel. it is, therefore, not possible to identify the specific funding for RNR training.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-11-01T17:38:01.987Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619856/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619856/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619856/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-24","Royal Naval Reserve","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what funding his Department has allocated for training members of the Royal Naval Reserve in each of the last five years; and what the projected funding for such training is for each of the next five years.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","49858"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619857","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-28","<p>The Royal Navy Reserve utilises various initiatives aimed at improving retention. These range from improved leave and financial provision, through to maximizing training opportunities and Divisional support.</p><p>Central to this is an improved offer, which includes better training, better equipment, improved remuneration and an improved experience for Reservists. We have also widened the opportunity for Reservists to contribute on operations. As a result, more Reservists are joining either as new entrants to the military, or with prior experience either in the Regulars or in the Reserves.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-10-28T13:35:57.813Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619857/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619857/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619857/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-24","Royal Naval Reserve","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps he is taking to improve the level of retention in the Royal Naval Reserve.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","49856"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619858","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-01","<p>The value of direct contracts alone that the Ministry of Defence (MOD) currently holds with suppliers in Wales is £6.957 billion. This value is based on direct contracts currently held where the prime location of work is identified as Wales, and also includes the share of other contracts where some work is identified as taking place in Wales.</p><p>The value excludes any work that we have been able to identify as having been sub-contracted to other locations, even where the main supplier is situated in Wales. It also excludes contracts with MOD Trading Funds; miscellaneous payments; pan-Government enabling contracts and other enabling contracts that cover the whole of the MOD estate.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-11-01T16:43:53.353Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619858/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619858/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619858/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-24","Ministry of Defence: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the value of current contracts is between his Department and suppliers based in Wales.","false","Biography information for Chris Elmore","Ogmore","Chris Elmore","49851"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619860","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-28","<p>As set out in Future Reserves 2020, the Royal Navy Reserve continues to be an integral part of the Royal Navy, conducting a wide range of operations and tasking.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-10-28T13:35:35.26Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619860/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619860/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619860/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-24","Royal Naval Reserve","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what assessment he has made of the capacity of the Royal Naval Reserve to support the Royal Navy in meeting its current operational commitments.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","49867"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619861","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-01","<p>I hold regular discussions with my counterpart, HRH Prince Mohammed bin Salman Al Saud, on a range of defence and security issues. The Saudi Arabian government has been a leading partner in international efforts to defeat Daesh.</p><p>Saudi Arabia co-leads the Global Coalition's work to cut Daesh's resources and established the Islamic Military Coalition to Fight Terrorism.</p>","Sevenoaks","Sir Michael Fallon",,"2016-11-01T16:29:57.307Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619861/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619861/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619861/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-24","Middle East: Islamic State","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what discussions he has had with his counterpart in Saudi Arabia on dealing with the threat posed by Daesh activities in the Middle East.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","49868"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619862","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-31","<p>The Secretary of State for Defence has met his Iraqi counterpart and Coalition partners, and has discussed the operations to defeat Daesh. The Iraqi-led operation to recapture Mosul is a vital part of the overall campaign against Daesh in the region. Coalition partners are aware of the importance of a comprehensive operation that will take all action necessary to degrade and defeat Daesh.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-10-31T17:07:29.627Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619862/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619862/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619862/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-24","Iraq: Islamic State","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what discussions his Department has held with (a) the Iraqi government and (b) other governments in that region on blocking the route between Mosul and the Syrian border which Daesh forces could use to escape Mosul.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","49918"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619863","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-01","<p>The battle for Mosul is a vital step in the defeat of Daesh in Iraq.</p><p>The UK is contributing as a member of the Global Counter-Daesh Coalition and welcomes all contributions made by other members of the Coalition in support of the Government of Iraq's offensive to regain the city.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-11-01T16:45:43.257Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619863/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619863/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619863/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-24","Iraq: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what assessment his Department was made of the effect that Turkish troops fighting in Iraq have had on the battle to regain Mosul.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","49919"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619865","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-31","<p>The Maritime Task Group will be tailored for each task. While the precise number and mix of vessels deployed would be dictated by the prevailing operational circumstances, we could draw from a range of modern and highly capable vessels including the Queen Elizabeth Class aircraft carriers, with embarked F-35B Lightning II and helicopters, surface combatants, submarines and logistic support shipping.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-10-31T17:07:03.437Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619865/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619865/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619865/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-24","Warships","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what his Department considers to be the standard composition of the maritime task group outlined in the 2015 Strategic Defence and Security Review.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","49920"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619866","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-31","<p>The Ministry of Defence has a forward purchase programme for foreign currency, using services provided by the Bank of England as agent for HM Treasury's Exchange Equalisation Account. This provides the Department with a degree of price stability that is currently mitigating the effect of the sterling rate on the Department's costs.</p>","Sevenoaks","Sir Michael Fallon",,"2016-10-31T17:06:38.17Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619866/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619866/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619866/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-24","Ministry of Defence: Gold and Foreign Exchange Reserves","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether his Department holds any foreign currency reserves.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","49921"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619867","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-28","<p>The Ministry of Defence does not notify the coroner when a deceased military person is repatriated from Scotland to England or Wales. In these instances registering the death with the appropriate coroner would routinely be undertaken by the Funeral Home appointed by the family.</p><p>Once a coroner has been identified, the Defence Inquests Unit will write to the coroner (in its capacity as the Ministry of Defence's single point of contact to Coroners) to establish whether an inquest into the death of the deceased is likely to take place.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-10-28T13:35:06.91Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619867/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619867/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619867/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-24","Armed Forces: Coroners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps his Department takes to notify the appropriate coroner when the body of a deceased military person is repatriated to England or Wales from Scotland for burial or cremation at the wishes of the family.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","49922"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619868","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-31","<p>Ministry of Defence officials will consult the organisations who are a party to the protocol for liaison on Fatal Accident Inquiries and I will write to the hon. Member once that consultation on publication has taken place.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-10-31T16:57:09.003Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619868/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619868/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619868/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-24","Armed Forces: Coroners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will publish the protocol between the Ministry of Justice, the Ministry of Defence, the Scottish Government and the Chief Coroner on dealing with military deaths in Scotland.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","49923"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619870","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-31","<p>The £9.2 billion planned savings will be delivered from: military and civilian pay restraint, reductions to the civilian headcount, the ending of military commitment bonuses, reductions in travel expenditure and professional fees, re-prioritisation of £2 billion of existing funding and further efficiencies within the Equipment Programme.</p>","Sevenoaks","Sir Michael Fallon",,"2016-10-31T17:05:39.527Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619870/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619870/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619870/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-24","Ministry of Defence: Cost Effectiveness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to page three of the National Audit Office report, Departmental Overview 2015-16, Ministry of Defence, published on 21 October 2016, from which budget headings the £9.2 billion of planned savings referred to in that report will be made.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","49886"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619871","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-27","<p>The Ministry of Defence has put in place a strategy to provide an alternative contractor should CarillionAmey fail to sustain the performance improvements made during the beginning of the year. The Department continues to assess CarillionAmey's performance to determine whether the implementation of this strategy is necessary.</p><p>The Department is committed to engaging with Service personnel and their families via Continuous Attitude Surveys, focus groups and bespoke surveys, as well as use of social media, to help inform and shape personnel policy. There are also regular meetings with the Families Federations.</p><p>We liaise with the Families Federations, when developing requirements for new accommodation contracts and they are actively engaged in developing the Future Accommodation Model.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-10-27T15:16:50.483Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619871/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619871/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619871/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-24","Armed Forces: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to the National Audit Office report, Departmental Overview 2015-16, Ministry of Defence, published on 21 October 2016, page 17, what steps he is taking to address dissatisfaction among service personnel with the standard of service family accommodation.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","49897"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619872","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-01","<p>The Ministry of Defence plans to deliver £2.1 billion of new efficiency savings over the Spending Review period by: driving a better service in Defence Equipment and Support; delivering savings following from the establishment of the Single Source Regulations Office and continuing the current Equipment Support Costs review.</p>","Sevenoaks","Sir Michael Fallon",,"2016-11-01T16:30:42.227Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619872/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619872/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619872/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-24","Ministry of Defence: Cost Effectiveness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to page 11 of the National Audit Office report, Departmental Overview 2015-16, Ministry of Defence, published on 21 October 2016, if he will provide further details of the £2.1 billion planned savings from improved commercial terms in the Equipment Plan.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","49887"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619874","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-01","<p>The £2 billion was centrally held headroom noted in the NAO Major Projects Report 2015 and the Equipment Plan 2015 to 2016. Together with the planned efficiency programme which should deliver £7.2 billion of savings across the life of this Parliament, this will contribute to the planned £9.26 billion savings.</p>","Sevenoaks","Sir Michael Fallon",,"2016-11-01T16:31:50.327Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619874/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619874/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619874/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-24","Ministry of Defence: Cost Effectiveness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to page 11 of the National Audit Office report, Departmental Overview 2015-16, Ministry of Defence, published on 21 October 2016, how the reprioritisation of £2 billion of existing funding contributes to his Department's planned savings of £9.2 billion.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","49888"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619875","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-08","<p>It was confirmed during the Spending Review that the Government would fund public sector pay awards at 1% for four years from 2016-17 onwards. This has reduced budget expenditure under the headings &quot;Service personnel costs&quot; and civilian personnel costs&quot; as described in the NAO report.</p>","Sevenoaks","Sir Michael Fallon",,"2016-11-08T15:59:15.547Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619875/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619875/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619875/answer","Sevenoaks","Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619875/answer/previousversion/17856","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-24","Ministry of Defence: Cost Effectiveness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to page 11 of the National Audit Office report, Departmental Overview 2015-16, Ministry of Defence, published on 21 October 2016, from which budget headings the £2 billion planned savings from military and civilian pay restraint referred to in that report will be made.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","49889"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619876","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-27","<p>We are aware of the Russian deployment of a new air defence system. This underlines the importance of the Memorandum of Understanding signed last year between the Russian Federation and the US, acting on behalf of the global Counter-Daesh Coalition. UK aircraft operating over Syria in support of the global Coalition comply fully with the operating procedures in the Memorandum that are designed to prevent flight safety incidents.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-10-27T15:16:05.563Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619876/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619876/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619876/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-24","Syria: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what assessment he has made of the implications for his Department's policies of the deployment of an S-300 long-range air defence system to the Tartus area of Syria by the Russian government.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","49899"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619877","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-31","<p>Over the past five years, UK Armed Forces have provided support to the armed forces of Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates, Qatar, Kuwait and Oman both in-country and in the UK and continue to do so. These States have attended international defence training courses in the UK such as the advanced command and staff course, Royal College of Defence Studies and Initial Officer Training.</p><p>UK Armed Forces have also provided training in-country through the delivery of tactical level Short Term Training Teams in the maritime, land and air domains. The Defence Academy has also delivered the Strategic Leadership Programme and Managing Defence in the Wider Security Context courses to Gulf States along with the Royal Navy's Exclusive Economic Zone Protection Officer course.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-10-31T17:06:11.813Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619877/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619877/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619877/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-24","Middle East: Military Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what training assistance his Department has provided to (a) Saudi Arabia, (b) the United Arab Emirates, (c) Qatar, (d) Kuwait and (e) Oman in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","49869"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619879","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-01","<p>The Mechanised Infantry Vehicle Project is in the early Concept Phase and has yet to reach Initial Gate. As such, it is too early to provide timescales, numbers or costs.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","49995 ; 49998 ; 50000","2016-11-01T16:49:00.373Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619879/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619879/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619879/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-24","Armoured Fighting Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many Mechanised Infantry Vehicles his Department is planning to procure in the next three years.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","49999"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619880","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-01","<p>The Challenger 2 Main Battle Tank remains a key capability for the British Army in the Government's Strategic Defence and Security Review 2015 and Joint Force 2025 plans, which will see the Army structured for a war-fighting division drawn from two Armoured Infantry Brigades and two Strike Brigades. As such the Ministry of Defence (MOD) is investing £53 million in the assessment phase of a Life Extension Programme with further funding allocated for a demonstration and manufacture phase. This will ensure that the Challenger 2 remains amongst the most capable Main Battle tanks in operation with any Army in the world until at least 2035. At this stage these plans do not include a replacement for the main armament but the MOD is open to innovative and affordable proposals that could improve the current capability.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","49979 ; 49980 ; 49997 ; 50001","2016-11-01T16:47:25.707Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619880/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619880/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619880/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-24","Challenger Tanks","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether his Department plans to reduce the army's total number of Challenger 2 main battle tanks.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","50002"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619881","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-01","<p>The Mechanised Infantry Vehicle Project is in the early Concept Phase and has yet to reach Initial Gate. As such, it is too early to provide timescales, numbers or costs.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","49995 ; 49999 ; 50000","2016-11-01T16:49:00.513Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619881/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619881/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619881/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-24","Armoured Fighting Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, when the new Mechanised Infantry Vehicle will reach initial operating capability.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","49998"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619882","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-31","<p>Whether the Convention applies would depend on the circumstances in which Reaper was to be used. Unmanned aerial systems are subject to the same operational accountability and oversight to that of manned aircraft, including the application of the War Powers Convention.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-10-31T17:02:28.533Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619882/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619882/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619882/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-24","Middle East: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what advice he has received on whether armed Reaper drones on missions outside Syria and Iraq are covered by the convention that Parliament has an opportunity to debate the circumstances in which armed forces are committed to military operations.","false","Biography information for Kirsten Oswald","East Renfrewshire","Kirsten  Oswald","49992"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619883","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-01","<p>The Mechanised Infantry Vehicle Project is in the early Concept Phase and has yet to reach Initial Gate. As such, it is too early to provide timescales, numbers or costs.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","49995 ; 49998 ; 49999","2016-11-01T16:49:00.59Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619883/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619883/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619883/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-24","Armoured Fighting Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what estimate he has made of the cost of the Mechanised Infantry Vehicle Programme.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","50000"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619885","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-01","<p>NATO will continue to remain the cornerstone of European defence and security and our decision to leave the EU will not undermine the prominent role that we play within the Alliance. Good progress has been made on delivering the NATO-EU co-operation announced at the Warsaw Summit and this was built firmly on the strong trans-Atlantic bond.</p>","Sevenoaks","Sir Michael Fallon",,"2016-11-01T17:03:29.713Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619885/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619885/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619885/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-24","Military Alliances: USA","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what assessment he has made of the potential effect on European and American defence co-operation of the withdrawal of the UK from the EU; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Kirsten Oswald","East Renfrewshire","Kirsten  Oswald","49993"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619886","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-27","<p>With the scale and complexity of the submarine programme, it is too early to be able to provide an estimate of the steel that could be supplied or manufactured by UK-based steel providers.</p><p> </p><p>BAE Systems, as the Prime Contractor, will manage the future steel procurements for the Dreadnought class submarines. We encourage British steel suppliers to take the opportunity to bid.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-10-27T15:15:25.737Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619886/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619886/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619886/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-24","Trident Submarines: Iron and Steel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 18 October 2016 to Question 48618, how much UK steel content will be secured through the 85 per cent BAE System supply chain in the UK.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","50016"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619887","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-01","<p>The Challenger 2 Main Battle Tank remains a key capability for the British Army in the Government's Strategic Defence and Security Review 2015 and Joint Force 2025 plans, which will see the Army structured for a war-fighting division drawn from two Armoured Infantry Brigades and two Strike Brigades. As such the Ministry of Defence (MOD) is investing £53 million in the assessment phase of a Life Extension Programme with further funding allocated for a demonstration and manufacture phase. This will ensure that the Challenger 2 remains amongst the most capable Main Battle tanks in operation with any Army in the world until at least 2035. At this stage these plans do not include a replacement for the main armament but the MOD is open to innovative and affordable proposals that could improve the current capability.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","49979 ; 49980 ; 49997 ; 50002","2016-11-01T16:47:26.02Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619887/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619887/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619887/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-24","Armoured Fighting Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether his Department plans to replace the 120mm L30A1 rifled tank gun with the Rheinmetall 120mm L55 smoothbore gun as part of the Challenger 2 Life Extension Programme.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","50001"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619888","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-31","<p>The Army's recruiting performance continues to get better, and the candidate's experience is improved through better communication processes, with improved processing and greater levels of candidate involvement. Inflow has increased year on year.</p><p>However, the delivery of the ICT has been further delayed, and approval has been requested for a revised Go-Live date of November 2017. Capita is working to deliver an earlier date of spring 2017 and I maintain a keen oversight of this issue.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-10-31T17:04:50.5Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619888/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619888/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619888/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-24","Army: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what recent progress his Department has made in the Army Recruiting Partnership Project; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Oliver Colvile","Plymouth, Sutton and Devonport","Oliver Colvile","49994"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619890","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-01","<p>The Mechanised Infantry Vehicle Project is in the early Concept Phase and has yet to reach Initial Gate. As such, it is too early to provide timescales, numbers or costs.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","49998 ; 49999 ; 50000","2016-11-01T16:49:00.45Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619890/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619890/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619890/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-24","Armoured Fighting Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to paragraph 4.48 of the National Security Strategy and Strategic Defence and Security Review 2015, Cm 9161, what estimate he has made of how many new Mechanised Infantry Vehicles will be in each of the Army's new strike brigades.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","49995"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619891","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-31","<p>Reapers (whether armed or not) are remotely piloted aircraft and, as such, they cannot themselves be &quot;armed forces&quot; for the purposes of the Armed Forces Act 2006 but those who pilot them on operations overseas will be.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-10-31T17:01:53.177Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619891/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619891/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619891/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-24","Unmanned Air Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether armed Reaper drones engaged in operations overseas are part of the armed forces for the purposes of the Armed Forces Act 2006.","false","Biography information for Kirsten Oswald","East Renfrewshire","Kirsten  Oswald","49990"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619892","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-01","<p>AJAX will form the core of the Army's new strike capability. Work is on-going to determine the exact requirements of the vehicles and equipment levels for the brigades providing this capability.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-11-01T16:41:20.277Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619892/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619892/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619892/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-24","Armoured Fighting Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to paragraph 4.48 of the National Security Strategy and Strategic Defence and Security Review 2015, Cm 9161, what estimate he has made of how many new Ajax armoured vehicles will be in each of the Army's new strike brigades.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","49996"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619893","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-31","<p>Whether UK pilots in control of Reaper unmanned aerial system conducting operations overseas are engaged in an armed conflict depends on the type of operation the pilots are undertaking. UK military personnel who are using force on overseas operations will do so in accordance with the laws of war (also known as the Law of Armed Conflict/International Humanitarian Law).</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-10-31T17:01:24.913Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619893/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619893/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619893/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-24","Unmanned Air Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether pilots who are in control of armed Reaper drones conducting operations overseas are (a) engaged in armed conflict and (b) regulated by the laws of war.","false","Biography information for Kirsten Oswald","East Renfrewshire","Kirsten  Oswald","49991"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619895","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-27","<p>There is no requirement to install water meters in properties where the Ministry of Defence (MOD) is responsible for the supply and there are no plans to change this policy.</p><p>The MOD follows the Water Resale Order 2006 which protects customers in private water resale situations from being overcharged or otherwise disadvantaged. The MOD follows these guidelines in its charging policy. MOD policy ensures that individual household bills do not exceed the average Statutory Undertaker household bill for the region.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-10-27T15:14:36.567Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619895/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619895/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619895/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-24","Armed Forces: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will make it his Department's policy that people living in property where his Department is responsible for the supply should have the option to have water meters installed.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","50014"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619896","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-01","<p>The Challenger 2 Main Battle Tank remains a key capability for the British Army in the Government's Strategic Defence and Security Review 2015 and Joint Force 2025 plans, which will see the Army structured for a war-fighting division drawn from two Armoured Infantry Brigades and two Strike Brigades. As such the Ministry of Defence (MOD) is investing £53 million in the assessment phase of a Life Extension Programme with further funding allocated for a demonstration and manufacture phase. This will ensure that the Challenger 2 remains amongst the most capable Main Battle tanks in operation with any Army in the world until at least 2035. At this stage these plans do not include a replacement for the main armament but the MOD is open to innovative and affordable proposals that could improve the current capability.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","49979 ; 49980 ; 50001 ; 50002","2016-11-01T16:47:25.927Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619896/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619896/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619896/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-24","Armoured Fighting Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what estimate he has made of the cost of the Challenger 2 Life Extension Programme.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","49997"
